# Cloud Agents / Cursor Web — token-aware + safety guardrails

## Purpose

Use Cloud Agents as a **toil offload** and **reproducible sandbox**, not as a replacement for:

- LAB-OP (operator LAN via SSH),
- `docs/private/` / `P:` workflows,
- or secret-bearing operations.

## Default stance (token-aware)

- Prefer **light gates** by default:
  - `uv sync`
  - `uv run pre-commit run --all-files`
  - a **targeted** `pytest` subset only when needed
- Avoid running heavy gates on every refresh:
  - `.\scripts\check-all.ps1` is for **pre-PR / pre-merge / pre-release** moments.

## Environment limitations (avoid false positives/negatives)

Cloud Agents may differ from the operator workstation:

- OS (Linux vs Windows), shells (bash vs PowerShell), and available system packages
- no access to operator LAN / homelab SSH targets (unless explicitly bridged)
- no access to `docs/private/` values (gitignored) unless explicitly provided

Treat failures as **signal to investigate**, not as proof of regression until reproduced in the right environment.

## Secrets and sensitive data (hard rule)

- Never put secrets in:
  - update/setup scripts
  - committed files
  - PR descriptions
- If a task requires secrets, use:
  - CI secret store / environment variables
  - or operator-controlled manual steps documented in `docs/private/`

## Recommended “Update Script” (minimal)

Use scripts as the repo’s “API” where possible.

### Minimal refresh (default)

```bash
uv sync
uv run pre-commit run --all-files
```

### Add tests (only when needed)

```bash
uv sync
uv run pre-commit run --all-files
uv run pytest -q
```

## What Cloud Agents are good for

- docs refactors, link fixes, markdown lint
- Python refactors guarded by unit tests
- pre-commit and CI-like checks in a clean sandbox
- draft PR descriptions / summaries

## What Cloud Agents should NOT do

- LAB-OP SSH actions (unless explicitly requested to run via the operator workstation terminal)
- any action that depends on private inventory values
- any destructive actions (mass deletes, force pushes, infra changes) without explicit operator intent

## Optional Slack `#data-boar-ops` mission log (operator-requested)

When the operator wants **audit-trail style** updates aligned with **`#data-boar-ops`**, follow **`.cursor/rules/slack-mission-log-protocol.mdc`** (situational — **`@slack-mission-log-protocol.mdc`** if globs miss). **Never** put webhook URLs or tokens in tracked files. Cloud Agents usually **cannot POST to Slack** without a configured Slack-capable tool or an operator-run step with **`SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL`** in env — if posting is impossible, **emit the formatted block in chat** so the operator can paste once.

